      "content": "Here’s a clean and practical versioning strategy tailored for your AI-integrated codebase with prompt-driven logic and a UI frontend (like a game using AI):✅ Recommended Versioning Scheme: MAJOR.MINOR.PROMPT.UIThis keeps your system simple, stable, and traceable across AI model prompt changes and frontend updates.🧱 Version Format:X.Y.Z.UWhere:X (Major) — Breaking architectural changes (e.g., new AI model or major game system overhaul).Y (Minor) — New features or flow changes that are backward compatible (e.g., new in-game action types, new prompt category).Z (Prompt Patch) — Changes to prompts or prompt logic that affect AI behavior/output.U (UI Patch) — Pure UI or UX changes (e.g., frontend visuals, layout adjustments).Let’s say you’re currently at version 1.3.4.2:ChangeResulting VersionUpdate LLM prompt for NPC dialogue1.3.5.2Add new AI-powered quest system1.4.0.0Revamp frontend battle UI only1.4.0.1Migrate to GPT-5 from GPT-42.0.0.0📦 Folder Structure & Tracking TipsStore prompts as separate files with version tags (e.g., npc_dialogue.v1.3.5.txt).Use Git tags like:v1.4.2.1 → easily reference full history across back-end and front-end.If you’re using GitHub or GitLab, maintain a simple changelog.md to track:Prompt edits with diff notesUI adjustmentsReason for version bump🧠 Why This Works for AI-Driven ProjectsAI behavior often changes significantly with prompt edits—this lets you track and roll back easily.Avoids version chaos where everything is “1.0” but user behavior differs drastically.Separates AI logic from UI changes, which helps teams work independently and reduce merge issues. help me build this into my project also update the readme explaining all this. also lets organize our tests, folder structure and what not also indicate which test to run when. like can you automatically wake up which tests to run when we make changes? the output of the test should be in folder that we are also going to check in as a part of project. each tests need